# Use Case Documents

- Write `usecases.md` in **simple English (B2)** — see `.cursor/rules/english-simple-b2-documents.mdc`.
- Describe concrete ways a user works with the feature.
- Focus on user context, user goal, and what the system must support.
- Keep the document clear, practical, and easy to scan.

- Use this structure for every use case:
  - `## Use Case N: [Short, concrete title]`
  - `**Actor:** ...`
  - `**Trigger:** ...`
  - `**What needs to be supported:**`

- In `Actor`:
  - use a concrete role, e.g. business owner, dispatcher, office worker,
  - use system or integration actors only when they are truly relevant.

- In `Trigger`:
  - describe briefly when and why this use case starts,
  - focus on the user need that initiates the flow.

- In `What needs to be supported`:
  - write bullet points,
  - start points with verbs,
  - make every point testable,
  - describe what the user must be able to do, not how it is implemented.

- Avoid:
  - technical details,
  - UI descriptions pixel by pixel,
  - long narrative paragraphs,
  - `Example Scenarios` sections.

- Good outcome:
  - all use cases together clearly show the main ways the feature is used.
